explanation:
isasciidigit: MHD_str_to_uint64_n_ directly calls isasciidigit; to prove the target does not violate the MISRA rule you must inspect this callee (and any functions it calls) to ensure it does not itself call memcmp or any string-comparison wrapper that uses memcmp.

memcmp: the MISRA rule specifically prohibits using the Standard Library memcmp to compare null-terminated strings. Include the memcmp symbol so the analyzer can recognize direct or indirect uses (calls, macro wrappers, or function pointers) of the standard memcmp in the target or its transitive callees.
